<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">WWC019</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Achievement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> All 3As</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Achievement for All 3As</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Achievement for All (3As) Ltd is a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n independent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">charity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">established in May 2011,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with the mission to transform the lives of vulnerable children, young people and their families, by raising their educational aspirations, access and achievement.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The charity is led by its Chair,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><a href="http://www.afa3as.org.uk/the-charity/trustees/brian-lamb"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Brian Lamb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">OBE</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, author of the Lamb </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Inquiry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pecial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ducational </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eeds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (SEN)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arental </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">onfidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><a href="http://www.afa3as.org.uk/the-charity/afa-3as-team/professor-sonia-blandford"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Professor Sonia </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Blandford</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, CEO and National Director of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> DfE funded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Achievement for All programme.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are currently over 1600 schools involved in the Achievement for All programme. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ollowing the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">profound impa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ct of the Achievement for All </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pilot </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2009-2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> involving 454 schools, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">10 local authorities in England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the programme is being rolled out nationally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Charity is also developing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and delivering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a number of other innovative interventions for s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hools in the UK and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nternationally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to improve outcomes of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disadvantaged children, those with SEN and other vulnerable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">children. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submission to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Education Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Inquiry into underachievement in white working class children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">: </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In broad terms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Achievement for All 3As </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">supports a framework in schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all vulnerable and disadvantaged children and young people can develop their skills, interests and capabilities to achieve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Achievement for All welcomes this opportunity to provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a response </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to the Education Committee on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inquiry into underachievement in education by white working class children. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The extent of white working class pupils’ educational underachievement.</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government data and research highlight underperformance in white, British pupils from socio-economically disadvantaged families</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. In 2012, white British pupils claiming FSM performed worse than any other group in the standard GCSE benchmark. 31% attained 5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> GCSEs, grades A*- C in comparison to 63% of white British pupils not claiming FSM. The attainment gap of 31% was the largest between the richest and poorest children of all ethnic groups. For Bangladeshi pupils, this figure was 6%, the smallest attainment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> gap between rich and poor children in any ethnic group (DfE, 2013, cited in Ofsted, 2013, p.28). Underlying data shows that Chinese children claiming FSM performed better than white British pupils not claiming free school meals.  For other ethnic groups t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he attainment gap has also improved at a faster rate over the last five years than for white British pupils. In 2012, the performance of all white British pupils in English and maths was below national average (Ofsted, 2013). The impact of social disadvant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">age is seen even before a child starts infant school. In 2012 52% of young children claiming FSM did not meet the expected level of development at the end of Early Years Foundation Stage; this compared to 33% of their more advantaged peers (DfE, 2013). </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here is a big overlap between pupils who are eligible for FSM and those who are identified as SEN. In January 2013, 17.4% of white British pupils across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">schools in England were identified with special educational needs (SEN, without a statement). This was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">higher than for Irish, Asian, Indian, Bangladeshi and Chinese pupils (Chinese pupils were the least likely ethnic group to be identified as SEN without a statement; they are also the highest performing ethnic group at GCSE level) (DfE, 2013b). The Lamb inq</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uiry (DCSF, 2009) questioned the accuracy of some schools in identifying children as SEN. Over identification of children </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">can</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">highlight</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a lack in teacher/school expectations.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Factors responsible for white working class educational underachievement, inclu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ding impact of home and family</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The causes of underachievement are multi-factorial. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Evidence suggests that socio-economic disadvantage is one reason for academic underachievement, but is not the only one. However, socio-economic disadvantage seems to have a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> stronger negative impact on white children than it does on most other ethnic groups. Chinese children claiming FSM perform almost as well as Chinese children not claiming FSM (White et al., 2013). Over the last few years the attainment of many ethnic grou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ps has improved. This is also the case for those whose first language is not English (EAL pupils).Today pupils from Bangladesh outperform their white contemporaries; five years ago their performance was below that of their white peers. In a similar vein, f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ive years ago, white British pupils outperformed Black African pupils. Today, their performance is almost </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">commensurate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (Ofsted, 2013).   </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Other factors which limit the achievement of white British pupils are rooted in the home, school and local community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">environment. Research evidence highlights the better performance of children whose parents are engaged with their learning (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Harris and Goodall, 2007). There is a strong association between parental support and children’s educational achievement ( Desforges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Abouchaar, 2011; Harris and Goodall, 2007 and Goodallet al, 2011). For children from poor families, many parents do not realise they have a part to play in their children’s education (Blandford, 2012). For others, social factors limit their ability to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> engage with their children’s learning (White et al, 2013). Evidence from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Achievement for All </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programme has shown that when parents are engaged in this process, children’s academic and wider outcomes are raised. Through structured conversations between</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> parents, their child and teachers, parents and carers have become an ‘essential’ part of their child’s learning. Both parents and children are given a ‘voice’ in the learning process. Teachers have got to know the pupils better and have been able to alter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> classroom teaching, introduce interventions and set more meaningful targets collaboratively. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Research also shows that children and young people from disadvantaged families often have high aspirations for their future life, but they and their parents lac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">k the capacity to achieve it. (Carter-Wall and Whtifield, 2012 and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Grayson, 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">). What they need in particular, is information on what is available and how to achieve it. Further research places the burden on schools, suggesting that it is schools which n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eed to help parents to understand what they need to do to meet their children’s aspirations (Menzies, 2013). </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is the problem worse for white British boys than white British girls? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Educational underachievement is a problem for both white working class boys and girls. It is particularly acute for boys. In 2012, almost one in three white British boys eligible for free school meals failed to make expected progress (Level 4) in English a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd maths at age 11 (end of Key Stage 2). 79% of all other pupils achieved this level or above in English and maths at the end of the Key Stage; for white boys from poor families, this figure was 60%. The situation is worse when reading ability is taken int</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o consideration. White boys from poor families are less likely to have basic reading skills than their more advantaged peers. In 2012, 51% of white British boys eligible for FSM made the expected progress in reading, writing and maths in comparison to a na</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tional average of 74%. Regrettably, this attainment gap widens from 24% to 32% by the time white boys from poor families complete secondary education.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2012, 26% of white British boys from disadvantaged families achieved the standard 5 A*-C GCSEs or iGC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SEs. This compared to 58% of all other pupils. Although the attainment gap at GCSE level between disadvantaged white boys and all other pupils has remained static since 2011, it has increased by 0.5% since 2008. Sadly, pupils who fail to leave school with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">basic literacy and maths are also less likely to be in employment, education or training when they leave secondary school and are more likely to spend time in prison. Almost half (48%) of all prisoners are at or below the expected Level 4 for reading of an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 11 year old. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">GCSE performance data for 2012 suggests that although white British boys are the lowest performing group nationally, with 26% achieving the standard 5 A*-C GCSEs including English and maths, white British girls only perform marginally bette</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r. They are the third lowest performing group at GCSE level after white British boys and Black Caribbean boys. 32% of Black Caribbean boys achieved the standard GCSE expectation, whilst 32% of white British girls achieved this level. This means white Briti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sh girls are the lowest achieving group of girls. Therefore any steps to improve educational outcomes of poor white pupils should address the challenges faced by both girls and boys in this group.   </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What steps schools can take to improve the educational </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">outcomes and attainment of white working class pupils</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In high performing education systems there is greater equity; all children are provided with the opportunity for ‘quality’ education (OECD, 2012). Schools nationally need to focus on raising the achieve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ment of white working class children. The London Challenge, the Greater Manchester Challenge and the Black Country Challenge all provide evidence of raised pupil achievement when there is a clear focus in schools in underperforming areas.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> involves a focus on raising aspirations (teachers, parents and pupils), increasing access and increasing achievement. This is done through effective deployment of resources- leadership, quality teaching and learning, parental and carer engagement in child</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ren’s learning and behaviour and attendance. This mirrors the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Achievement for All</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> programme, a bespoke framework for schools, which through a collaborative approach, has enabled schools to successfully focus on aspirations, access and achievement to raise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pupil outcomes.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> In 2012, schools engaged in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Achievement for All</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> programme saw Average Point Score increases of 50% above the national average for pupils with SEN; for reading and writing the increase was 4.2 APS. For maths this figure was an increase of 3.8 APS. Findings across schools also showed a 17% improvement in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> parent and carer engagement with teachers and with their children’s learning; there was a 36% increase in schools reporting excellent relationships with parents and carers. In top performing  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Achievement for All</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> schools, i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ncreases of up to 330% in Average</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Point Scores of between 6.50 and 9.15 in reading, writing and math were found. Teachers reported an 11% improvement in the ‘effective use of teaching practices’ and an equivalent, 11% increase in confidence in teaching students with SEN. Student behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and attendance improved with a 9% improvement in student attendance and an 8% improvement in student </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. (PwC, 2013).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Prior attainment is the single most effective indicator of a child’s future achievement. A child who does not reach expected Leve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l 4 in English and maths, is also less likely to achieve 5 A*-C GCSEs. This single fact underlines the centrality of early intervention. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Never have head teachers in England had the autonomy they have today. They have more autonomy than head teachers in hi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gh performing countries (e.g. Singapore) (OECD, 2012). They have the autonomy to both identify low achieving groups and the autonomy to close the attainment gaps. Pupil Premium funding can be directed to where it is most needed. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The role of Government in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> delivering improved educational outcomes for white working class pupils</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many of the recent educational reforms have led to increased pupil attainment and progress. The government supports the national expansion of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Achievement for All</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Government still has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a strong role to play in ensuring that there is equity and quality in education for every child. This includes promoting a culture of high expectations acro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ss all schools and a focus nationally on educational outcomes of white working class boys and girls</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Key findings from Achievement for All pilot (2009-2011) (Humphrey and Squires, 2011)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">454 primary, secondary and s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pecial schools and pupil referral units across 10 local authorities in England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> participated in the Achievement for All pilot, with a cohort of 28,000 pupils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Key findings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">showed that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">37% of SEND pupils in Achievement for All pilot schools achieved or exceeded expected levels of progress in English compared to ALL pupils nationall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">42% of SEND pupils in the Achievement for All schools achieved or exceeded expected levels of progress in Maths compared to all pupils nationally.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A 10% drop in persistent absenteeism</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> across schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The number of Achievement for All schools reporting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that they now have excellent relationship</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s with parents increased by 36%.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>